[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926945&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926945&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

The domain system is fundamentally flawed becuase it does not
support inverse queries in a reasonable manner. The .in-addr.arpa is
a horrible kludge designed to cover up a fundamental design flaw.

There is nothing conceptually wrong with trying to identify the site that
is calling you. In fact, I claim it is a good idea in general.

You are seeing a flawed implementation, not a flawed concept. If the
arpanet response time was "reasonable" and the servers and resolvers
running "reasonably", then you would only see sub-second delays.
In fact, it works fine unless you need to talk to one of the root
servers.

--rick

